Regional Development in Italy: the North South Divide and the case of Calabria

Introduction

Diversification and the movement of labour out of agriculture and into high productivity manufacturing has been seen as an essential tool to raise productivity in a region and hence improving regional GDP. In Italy, regional inequalities have been exacerbated by a rise of manufacturing in the North and a lagging behind in terms of productivity in the South.

This essay examines the way in which Calabria in Southern Italy has failed to keep pace with aggregate growth in the country through the lens of evolutionary economic geography; focussing on the timing of the adoption of general purpose technologies, the space along which comparative advantages were generated, the pace of structural change and the kinds of spillovers affecting the region. The essay concludes by outlining a tool created to analyse these kinds of regional differentiations in Europe using data from the Ross-Wolf database on regional GDP.
